        return $data;
    }

    /**
     * @param  list<array{heading: string, paragraphs: list<string>, list?: list<string>}>  $sections
     */
    private static function article(string $keyword, string $intro, array $sections): string
    {
        $html = '<p>'.$intro.'</p>';
        $html .= '<p>This guide on <strong>'.$keyword.'</strong> helps Indian home buyers, investors, and NRIs protect themselves before paying token or registering property. Ocean Realtors coordinates verified listings and initial paperwork screening — contact us by phone or WhatsApp for support in Gurgaon and NCR.</p>';

        foreach ($sections as $section) {
            $html .= '<h2>'.htmlspecialchars($section['heading'], ENT_QUOTES, 'UTF-8').'</h2>';
            foreach ($section['paragraphs'] as $paragraph) {
                $html .= '<p>'.$paragraph.'</p>';
            }
            if (! empty($section['list'])) {
                $html .= '<ul>';
                foreach ($section['list'] as $item) {
                    $html .= '<li>'.$item.'</li>';
                }
                $html .= '</ul>';
            }
        }

        return $html;
    }

    private static function enrich(string $title, string $keyword, string $category): string
    {
        $faqs = self::faqsFor($category);
        $faqHtml = '<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>';
        foreach ($faqs as $faq) {
            $faqHtml .= '<h3>'.$faq['q'].'</h3><p>'.$faq['a'].'</p>';
        }

        return <<<HTML
<h2>Documents Checklist by Property Type</h2>
<p>Requirements overlap but emphasis differs by asset class. Use this quick reference alongside your advocate's state-specific list.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Resale flat in society:</strong> Sale deed, EC, share certificate, society NOC, dues certificate, approved plan, OC where applicable</li>
<li><strong>Independent builder floor:</strong> Title chain, conversion if needed, building plan sanction, OC/CC, property tax, no tenant occupancy</li>
<li><strong>Under-construction from builder:</strong> RERA registration, land title, agreement for sale, payment schedule, approved plans</li>
<li><strong>Plot / land:</strong> Revenue records, conversion order, layout sanction, EC, boundary survey, master plan zoning</li>
</ul>
<p>Buyers searching for guidance on {$keyword} should map their shortlist to the correct column above — then verify each line item with originals, not WhatsApp photos alone.</p>

<h2>NRI and Remote Buyers: Extra Paperwork Care</h2>
<p>NRIs and out-of-city buyers often rely on PoA holders for site visits and signing. PoA must be specific, registered where required, and paired with the same document bundle an on-site buyer would demand. Remote purchase without EC and title review is how NRI fraud cases multiply — video walkthroughs do not replace legal search.</p>

<h2>After Registration: Documents to Retain</h2>
<p>Post-registration, maintain registered sale deed, stamp duty receipt, society transfer confirmation, updated property tax, and loan closure/NOC when applicable. These papers support future resale, tax filing, and loan top-up. Scan and store originals in a fire-safe location.</p>

<h2>Why Document Verification Cannot Be Skipped</h2>
<p>Indian property law relies heavily on registered documents and public records. A seller's assurance — or a broker's "clean deal" claim — does not replace an encumbrance certificate, title chain review, and approval checks. Buyers who skip verification to win a negotiation often spend years and lakhs fixing problems that paper review would have surfaced in days.</p>
<p>When your focus is {$keyword}, treat document verification as part of the purchase price — not an optional extra after token.</p>

<h2>State-Wise Variations Buyers Should Know</h2>
<p>Land record names, online portal availability, stamp duty rates, and EC procedures differ by state — Haryana, Delhi NCR, Maharashtra, Karnataka, and others each have distinct formats. An advocate licensed in the property's state should lead final diligence even if you live elsewhere or buy remotely as an NRI.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Haryana / Gurgaon:</strong> RERA Haryana, jamabandi-style records, society NOC culture for flats</li>
<li><strong>Delhi:</strong> MCD property tax, conversion and layout rules vary by zone</li>
<li><strong>General:</strong> Always match property description exactly across deed, EC, and tax records</li>
</ul>

<h2>Token Payment and Legal Conditions</h2>
<p>If you pay token before full verification, use a written agreement stating refund if legal clearance fails. Prefer traceable bank transfers over cash. Cap token at a modest amount until advocate report is satisfactory. Never register Power of Attorney in favour of strangers without independent legal advice.</p>

<h2>Role of Banks vs Your Advocate</h2>
<p>Home loan legal teams verify documents for the lender's interest — not necessarily every risk affecting your ownership or resale. Hire your own property advocate for buyer-side diligence even when the bank runs parallel review. Both reviews together provide stronger protection.</p>

<h2>Physical Inspection Alongside Paper Review</h2>
<p>Documents can be clean while the property has unapproved construction, occupancy by third parties, or society disputes. Visit the property, speak to neighbours and society office, and match built structure to approved plans. Paper and physical diligence together form complete due diligence.</p>

<h2>Timeline: When to Verify What</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Before site visit:</strong> Preliminary title and RERA screen if under-construction</li>
<li><strong>Before token:</strong> Advocate review of core title, EC, and approvals</li>
<li><strong>After agreement:</strong> Society NOC, loan legal, final sale deed draft</li>
<li><strong>Before registration:</strong> Stamp duty, final dues clearance, bank lien coordination</li>
</ul>

<h2>Red Flags That Should Pause the Deal</h2>
<ul>
<li>Seller refuses to share EC or prior deeds</li>
<li>POA seller unrelated to owner without clear succession</li>
<li>Missing OC on occupied multi-storey building</li>
<li>Society confirms litigation or transfer freeze</li>
<li>Plot sold without visible conversion / CLU documentation</li>
<li>Pressure to pay large cash component without disclosure</li>
</ul>

<h2>How Ocean Realtors Helps Buyers</h2>
<p>Ocean Realtors supports Gurgaon and NCR buyers with verified shortlists, society comparisons, and initial paperwork screening before you engage your advocate for full legal due diligence. We help you avoid obviously risky listings early — saving time and token exposure — while your lawyer completes formal title certification.</p>
<p>For personalised guidance on {$title}, contact Ocean Realtors by phone or WhatsApp. We respond within two business hours (Mon–Sat, 10 AM–7 PM) with structured next steps.</p>

{$faqHtml}

<h2>Final Reminder</h2>
<p>Property purchases are irreversible once registered with defects. Invest in document verification early — it is the cheapest insurance in real estate. Whether you buy a flat, floor, or plot, let verified papers — not urgency — guide your decision.</p>
HTML;
    }

    /**
     * @return list<array{q: string, a: string}>
     */
    private static function faqsFor(string $category): array
    {
        $common = [
            ['q' => 'Can I verify property documents myself without a lawyer?', 'a' => 'You can screen basic documents — sale deed, EC request, RERA registration — but final purchase decisions should rely on a property advocate\'s written opinion. Self-review misses legal nuances in chain, POA, and approval gaps.'],
            ['q' => 'How long does property document verification take?', 'a' => 'Preliminary review may take 3–7 working days; complex title or plot matters can take 2–3 weeks. Start diligence before token, not after.'],
            ['q' => 'What is the cost of legal due diligence in India?', 'a' => 'Advocate fees vary by city and complexity — often from a few thousand rupees for straightforward flats to higher amounts for plots or disputed chains. The cost is small relative to property value and risk avoided.'],
        ];

        $specific = match ($category) {
            'encumbrance_cert' => [
                ['q' => 'How many years of EC should I obtain?', 'a' => 'Lenders often require 13–30 years depending on state and loan policy. For cash purchases, follow your advocate\'s recommendation — typically at least 13 years or longer for older properties.'],
            ],
            'rera_docs' => [
                ['q' => 'Is RERA registration enough to guarantee safe purchase?', 'a' => 'RERA reduces certain developer risks but does not replace title review of land, approved plans, or your agreement terms. Verify RERA plus full legal diligence.'],
            ],
            'document_frauds' => [
                ['q' => 'What should I do if I suspect forged documents?', 'a' => 'Stop payment immediately, consult a property lawyer, and consider reporting to local police and consumer/RERA forums. Do not proceed without independent registry verification.'],
            ],
            'land_records', 'plot_docs' => [
                ['q' => 'Are online land records sufficient for plot purchase?', 'a' => 'Online records help preliminary screening but plot purchases require conversion orders, boundary verification, and advocate title search before token.'],
            ],
            default => [
                ['q' => 'Should I pay token before document verification?', 'a' => 'Best practice is to complete advocate review first or pay a small refundable token tied to legal clearance. Large tokens before verification expose you to avoidable risk.'],
            ],
        };

        return array_merge($specific, $common);
    }
}
